> **Note:** These are rule IDs/levels/descriptions as displayed by the Wazuh Dashboard during testing — not the raw rule XML. To get the actual rule logic behind these IDs, pull the corresponding entries from your Wazuh Manager, e.g.:
> ```bash
> sudo grep -r "92041" /var/ossec/ruleset/rules/
> sudo grep -r "92041" /var/ossec/etc/rules/local_rules.xml
> ```
> Copy the matched `<rule>` blocks into `detection-rules/local_rules.xml` (sanitized of any host-specific info) so the repo shows your actual detection logic, not just the dashboard output.

## Custom Rules Template
Use this as the starting shell for any custom rules you write going forward — save as `detection-rules/local_rules.xml`:

```xml
<!-- Local rules — placed in /var/ossec/etc/rules/local_rules.xml -->
<!-- Group IDs 100000-999999 are reserved for custom/local rules -->

<group name="local,syslog,sshd,">

  <rule id="100100" level="10">
    <if_group>syscheck</if_group>
    <field name="file">SOC-Lab</field>
    <description>Custom: Change detected inside the C:\SOC-Lab monitored test directory</description>
  </rule>

  <!-- Add additional custom rules here as you build them -->

</group>
```
